# What is this lab about?

In this lab we learn a new machine learning method called **Logistic Regression**.

Think of it like this:

> Imagine you are trying to guess if it will rain today.
> You look at clues — dark clouds? windy? cold?
> You combine all the clues and come up with a **score between 0 and 1**.
> If the score is above 0.5, you say "yes, it will rain."
> If it is below 0.5, you say "no, it will not rain."
>
> Logistic regression does exactly this — it looks at clues (columns in the
> data) and gives a **probability** (a number from 0 to 1) of something
> happening. Here, the "something" is: *did this Titanic passenger survive?*

---

# Key Topics

- What logistic regression is and how it is different from decision trees
- Cleaning data before building a model (fixing empty values)
- Building a logistic regression model with `glm()`
- Converting a **probability** into a **yes/no prediction** using a threshold
- Measuring model quality: **accuracy**, **precision**, **recall**
- Understanding the **ROC curve** and **AUC**
- What happens when you change the threshold
- Why missing values (`NA`) are a problem for logistic regression

---

# Step 1 — Load packages and data

```r
library(titanic)      # the Titanic dataset
library(tidymodels)   # tools for model evaluation (roc_auc, roc_curve, etc.)

data(titanic_train)
head(titanic_train)
```

::: {.callout-note}
**tidymodels** is a collection of tools that makes it easier to build,
evaluate and compare machine learning models in R. We use it here mainly
for the ROC curve and AUC score.
:::

---

# Step 2 — Clean the data

```r
table(titanic_train$Embarked)
```

This counts how many passengers have each value in the `Embarked` column.
`Embarked` means "which port did they board the ship from?"
The values should be `C`, `Q`, or `S`.

```r
titanic_train[titanic_train$Embarked == "",]$Embarked = "S"
```

::: {.callout-important}
**Why are we doing this?**

Some passengers have an **empty string** `""` for `Embarked` — meaning the
data is missing. Logistic regression does not like missing or unexpected
values. We replace them with `"S"` (Southampton) because that was the most
common port — it is a reasonable guess.

> 🧒 It is like a form where someone left a field blank. We fill it in
> with the most common answer so the form is complete.
:::

---

# Step 3 — Split the data

```r
set.seed(42)
nobs  <- nrow(titanic_train)
train <- sample(nobs, 0.9 * nobs)
test  <- setdiff(seq_len(nobs), train)
```

Same as Lab 3 — 90% of rows go to **training** (the model learns from these),
10% go to **testing** (we check how well the model works on new data).
`set.seed(42)` makes sure we always get the same split.

---

# Step 4 — Choose which columns to use

```r
target       <- "Survived"
colsToIgnore <- c("PassengerId", "Name", "Cabin", "Ticket", "Age")
input        <- setdiff(names(titanic_train), c(target, colsToIgnore))
input
```

::: {.callout-warning}
**Why is `Age` excluded here — but not in Lab 3?**

Logistic regression **cannot handle missing values** (`NA`) at all.
If even one passenger in the test set has a missing age, the entire
`predict()` call will return `NA` for that row.

In Lab 3 (decision trees) we fixed this by **imputing** (filling in) the
missing ages. Here, the simpler fix is to just **leave `Age` out** of the
model entirely. Later in the lab we test what happens when we include it
— and we see the problem appear.

> 🧒 Imagine you are filling out a quiz but some answers are invisible.
> You cannot add up the score if some answers are missing.
> Logistic regression has the same problem.
:::

**Columns we keep as inputs:**
`Pclass`, `Sex`, `SibSp`, `Parch`, `Fare`, `Embarked`

```r
train_data <- titanic_train[train, c(input, target)]
test_data  <- titanic_train[test,  c(input, target)]
```

We create two separate data frames — one for training and one for testing.
This is cleaner than always writing `titanic_train[train, ...]` each time.

---

# Step 5 — Build the logistic regression model

```r
logistic_model <- glm(formula = Survived ~ .,
                      family  = binomial(link = "logit"),
                      data    = train_data)
summary(logistic_model)
logistic_model$coefficients
```

::: {.callout-note}
**Breaking this down piece by piece:**

| Part | Meaning |
|---|---|
| `glm()` | "Generalised Linear Model" — the R function for logistic regression |
| `Survived ~ .` | "Predict `Survived` using all other columns" |
| `family = binomial(link = "logit")` | "This is a yes/no prediction problem" |
| `data = train_data` | "Learn from the training data only" |

**What are coefficients?**

> 🧒 Think of coefficients as *weights* or *importance scores* for each clue.
> A large positive number means "this clue strongly suggests the person survived."
> A large negative number means "this clue strongly suggests they did not survive."
> A number close to zero means "this clue doesn't help much."

For example, you will likely see that `Sexmale` has a large **negative**
coefficient — being male strongly reduced the chance of survival on the Titanic.
:::

---

# Step 6 — Make predictions

## Get raw probabilities

```r
pr <- predict(logistic_model, newdata = test_data, type = "response")
pr
```

`type = "response"` tells R to give us **probabilities** (numbers between 0
and 1), not raw scores.

> 🧒 Each number is like saying: "I am 73% sure this person survived"
> or "I am 12% sure this person survived."

## Convert probabilities to yes/no using a threshold

```r
pr <- ifelse(pr > 0.5, 1, 0)
```

`ifelse()` says: **if** the probability is above 0.5, say `1` (survived).
**Otherwise**, say `0` (did not survive).

> 🧒 It is like saying: "If I am more than 50% sure it will rain,
> I will bring an umbrella. Otherwise I won't."

The **0.5** here is called the **threshold** — we will change it later
and see what happens.

---

# Step 7 — Evaluate the model

## Confusion matrix and accuracy

```r
actuals <- factor(test_data$Survived, levels = c(1, 0))
pr      <- factor(pr, levels = c(1, 0))

tab1 <- table(pr, actuals)
tab1

accuracy <- 100 * sum(diag(tab1) / sum(tab1))
accuracy
```

We wrap the values in `factor(..., levels = c(1, 0))` to tell R that
`1` (survived) is the **positive class** — the thing we most care about
predicting correctly.

::: {.callout-note}
**Confusion matrix reminder:**

|  | **Actual: Survived (1)** | **Actual: Died (0)** |
|---|---|---|
| **Predicted: Survived (1)** | ✅ True Positive (TP) | ❌ False Positive (FP) |
| **Predicted: Died (0)** | ❌ False Negative (FN) | ✅ True Negative (TN) |

- **Accuracy** = how often we were right overall
- But accuracy alone can be misleading! (More on this below)
:::

---

# Step 8 — ROC Curve and AUC

```r
pr <- predict(logistic_model, newdata = test_data, type = "response")
test_data$predicted <- pr
test_data$Survived  <- factor(test_data$Survived, levels = c(1, 0))

auc <- roc_auc(test_data, Survived, predicted)
auc

roc <- roc_curve(test_data, Survived, predicted)
autoplot(roc)
```

::: {.callout-note}
**What is a ROC curve?**

> 🧒 Imagine your model is a security guard at the door of a "survivors only"
> club. If the guard is very strict (high threshold), they only let in people
> they are almost 100% sure survived — but they will turn away some real
> survivors by mistake. If the guard is very relaxed (low threshold), they
> let almost everyone in — but some non-survivors sneak in too.
>
> The ROC curve **draws a picture of this trade-off** for every possible
> threshold at once.

**What is AUC?**

AUC = "Area Under the Curve". It is a single number that summarises the
whole ROC curve.

| AUC Value | Meaning |
|---|---|
| 1.0 | Perfect model — always right |
| 0.5 | Useless model — no better than random guessing |
| 0.7 – 0.8 | Decent model |
| 0.8 – 0.9 | Good model |
| > 0.9 | Excellent model |
:::

## Precision-Recall curve

```r
pr_c <- pr_curve(test_data, Survived, predicted)
autoplot(pr_c)
```

::: {.callout-note}
**Precision vs Recall — what is the difference?**

These two measures tell you about *different types* of mistakes.

> 🧒 Imagine a doctor who tests patients for a disease:
>
> - **Precision** = "Of all the patients I said had the disease,
>   how many actually had it?" (How accurate are my positive predictions?)
> - **Recall** = "Of all the patients who actually had the disease,
>   how many did I catch?" (Did I miss anyone sick?)

In formulas:

$$
\text{Precision} = \frac{TP}{TP + FP}
$$

$$
\text{Recall} = \frac{TP}{TP + FN}
$$

There is always a **trade-off** between the two — which brings us to the
next section.
:::

---

# Step 9 — Changing the threshold

This is one of the most important parts of the lab. We run the same model
three times with **different thresholds** and compare the results.

## What is the threshold?

```r
pr <- ifelse(pr >= threshold, 1, 0)
```

The threshold is the cut-off point. If the model says the probability is
**above** the threshold, we predict "survived". Below it, we predict "died".

> 🧒 Imagine you are sorting packages at a post office.
> If a package feels *heavy enough*, you mark it "fragile — handle with care."
> The weight you choose as "heavy enough" is the threshold.
> Change that weight and different packages get marked.

## Threshold = 0.5 (default)

```r
threshold <- 0.5
```

Balanced — you need to be at least 50% sure before predicting survival.

## Threshold = 0.1 (very low)

```r
threshold <- 0.1
```

> 🧒 You only need to be 10% sure someone survived to predict they did.
> This means you will predict "survived" for **almost everyone**.
>
> - ✅ **High recall** — you will catch nearly all real survivors
> - ❌ **Low precision** — you will also wrongly predict survival for many
>   people who did not survive

## Threshold = 0.9 (very high)

```r
threshold <- 0.9
```

> 🧒 You need to be 90% sure before predicting survival.
> This means you will only say "survived" for passengers you are very
> confident about.
>
> - ✅ **High precision** — when you say "survived", you are almost always right
> - ❌ **Low recall** — you will miss many actual survivors

::: {.callout-important}
**The big trade-off:**

Lowering the threshold → catches more survivors, but makes more false alarms  
Raising the threshold → fewer false alarms, but misses more survivors

Which is better **depends on the problem**. In medical diagnosis, it is
usually worse to miss a sick patient (low recall) than to over-diagnose
(lower precision). In spam filters, it may be worse to block real emails
(lower precision) than to let some spam through.
:::

